<subSubSection pageId="31" pageNumber="32" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="31.[151,1437,1436,2039]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,1436,1462]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Male. Length 
<quantity box="[447,587,1436,1463]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.2" metricValueMax="9.9" metricValueMin="8.5" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" unit="mm" value="9.2" valueMax="9.9" valueMin="8.5">8.5–9.9 mm</quantity>
. Postocular plate with silvery pollinosity. Ocellar bristles well developed. Thorax mostly silvery pollinose, with some golden pollinosity on anepisternum. Four well-developed post-sutural dorsocentral bristles. Apical scutellar bristles absent. Legs blackish. Abdomen grayish with silvery pollinosity, contrasting with the golden pollinosity of T5. T3 with 1 pair of lateral marginal bristles, T4 with 1 pair of marginal lateral and without median marginal bristles. ST5 with deep median V-shaped cleft. Cercus slightly sinuous in lateral view, with pointed obliquely cut apex, dorsal subapical barb and subapical, pointed and latero-dorsal indentation. Cercus with bristles ventrally on proximal half. Cerci with distal third narrower than middle part in posterior view; parallel and with a distinct constriction mid length. Pregonite and postgonite with expanded base, gradually narrowing to apex; unicolorous. Distiphallus with smooth ventroapical margin, conical apex and sinuous dorsal outline. Juxta with microtrichose surface and anterior margin serrated. Vesica symmetrical; distal lobes well developed, sclerotized, broadened in apical half in lateral view, with smooth dorsal and ventral surfaces.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="31" pageNumber="32" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="31.[151,1437,1436,2039]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1832,1858]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Remarks.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Dufek, M. I. &amp; Mulieri, P. R." box="[321,591,1832,1858]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" pagination="917 - 924" refId="ref107089" refString="Dufek, M. I. &amp; Mulieri, P. R. (2017) Two new species of Oxysarcodexia Townsend (Diptera: Sarcophagidae) from the Chaco Forest Ecoregion of South America. Journal of Medical Entomology, 54 (4), 917 - 924. https: // doi. org / 10.1093 / jme / tjx 054" type="journal article" year="2017">Dufek &amp; Mulieri (2017)</bibRefCitation>
considered 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dufek &amp; Mulieri" authorityYear="2017" box="[724,837,1832,1858]" class="Insecta" family="Sarcophagidae" genus="Oxysarcodexia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="berthet">
<emphasis box="[724,837,1832,1858]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">O. berthet</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
a member of the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Dodge" baseAuthorityYear="1968" box="[1030,1070,1833,1858]" class="Insecta" family="Sarcophagidae" genus="Xarcophaga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="xon">
<emphasis box="[1030,1070,1833,1858]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">xon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group due to the elongate cercus and phallus (
<figureCitation box="[297,381,1868,1895]" captionStart="FIGURES 51–59" captionStartId="34.[151,264,1827,1851]" captionTargetBox="[180,1405,322,1774]" captionTargetId="figure-70@34.[151,1435,306,1804]" captionTargetPageId="34" captionText="FIGURES 51–59. Oxysarcodexia spp., males. 51–53. Oxysarcodexia berthet Dufek &amp; Mulieri (Argentina, MACN). 51. Habitus, lateral view. 52. Terminalia, lateral view. 53. Terminalia, posterior view. 54–56. Oxysarcodexia bicolor Lopes (Brazil, Rio de Janeiro, Petrópolis, NRM, except Fig. 54, Argentina, MACN). 54. Habitus, lateral view. 55. Terminalia, lateral view. 56. Terminalia, posterior view. 57–59. Oxysarcodexia bikini Dodge (Chile, Santiago, MNRJ, except Figs 57–58, Argentina, MACN). 57. Habitus, lateral view. 58. Terminalia, lateral view. 59. Terminalia, posterior view. Figs 51–54, 57–58 by P.R. Mulieri (MACN)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4405619" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4405619/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Fig. 52</figureCitation>
), although this is in conflict with the short juxta. The lateral, tooth-like process of the phallic tube is weakly pronounced and similar to that present in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lopes" baseAuthorityYear="1973" box="[787,935,1904,1930]" class="Insecta" family="Sarcophagidae" genus="Oxysarcodexia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="peruviana">
<emphasis box="[787,935,1904,1930]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">O. peruviana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and the sclerotized anterior juxtal margin is similar to that in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Souza &amp; Buenaventura" authorityYear="2016" box="[345,448,1940,1966]" class="Insecta" family="Sarcophagidae" genus="Oxysarcodexia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="catica">
<emphasis box="[345,448,1940,1966]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">O. catica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lopes" baseAuthorityYear="1946" box="[463,590,1940,1966]" class="Insecta" family="Sarcophagidae" genus="Oxysarcodexia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fraterna">
<emphasis box="[463,590,1940,1966]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">O. fraterna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Dufek &amp; Mulieri 2017)" baseAuthorityName="Dufek &amp; Mulieri" baseAuthorityYear="2017" box="[646,1025,1940,1966]" class="Insecta" family="Sarcophagidae" genus="Oxysarcodexia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ibera">
<emphasis box="[646,740,1940,1966]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">O. ibera</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Dufek, M. I. &amp; Mulieri, P. R." box="[755,1017,1940,1966]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" pagination="917 - 924" refId="ref107089" refString="Dufek, M. I. &amp; Mulieri, P. R. (2017) Two new species of Oxysarcodexia Townsend (Diptera: Sarcophagidae) from the Chaco Forest Ecoregion of South America. Journal of Medical Entomology, 54 (4), 917 - 924. https: // doi. org / 10.1093 / jme / tjx 054" type="journal article" year="2017">Dufek &amp; Mulieri 2017</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. Female unknown. See also remarks under 
<taxonomicName authority="Souza &amp; Pape &amp; Thyssen, 2020" authorityName="Souza &amp; Pape &amp; Thyssen" authorityYear="2020" box="[222,363,1976,2002]" class="Insecta" family="Sarcophagidae" genus="Oxysarcodexia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ariozanoi" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[222,363,1976,2002]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">O. ariozanoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[371,434,1976,2002]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[371,434,1976,2002]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
